q34: The upgrade of the exchange server has been a terrible experience--the connection has been spotty and the response time to fix the issue has been abysmal. It continues to be an issue at the heaviest traffic times that the email system lags and then my inbox fills with 20+ emails that had been sent over the last several hours that had not been received. This is not acceptable and needs to be resolved sooner than it is being resolved. Additionally, the survey did not ask about Adobe Connect. Adobe Connect is no longer meeting the needs of virtual classes and needs another solution ASAP.
Didn't have much to add as I am a returning student in my first semester back and take all my courses online.
add a progress bar to this survey so we know how much farther there is to go.thanks.

I think UITS services are fantastic.  I have had to call in for assistance twice in the past year, and the person that I spoke with was very polite, professional, and knowledgeable.  I do not like the discussion forums in Canvas, they were much easier to follow in Oncourse, but I have no other complaints about the switch.  Thanks for everything you do!

I've had a lot of trouble with Outlook.  Sometimes e-mail gets stuck in my Outbox and I have to reboot.  Sometimes I can't access out-of-office. Also, my lync/skype phone keeps turning the ringer off.  The reliability of the wireless network seems to be greatly improved since the last time I took this survey.

I got a Microsoft Suface via CAITS last year.  this is good device.  When I asked for help in learning Windows 8 several different CAITs staff replied "they would like help in learning Windows 8".   What I have learned about using this system has been on my own and in random fashion.  Like always Microsoft help is usually not helpful.

I think it would be useful to have a classroom teacher's orientation to the equipment in the classrooms, especially trouble shooting.  Also, design a means of making the use of Canvas in the classroom more user friendly.
The wireless network is not very strong on the 3rd floor of the library and on up in the library when I use my laptop or smartphone. That's my only dislike, but everything else is great!
the IT notice regarding the exchange upgrade has been listed as an issue now for 5 months.  I think it is time to fix the problem!

The printer in the Social work PhD lounge computer lab is awful. It's always printing gibberish, spitting out page after page of strange symbols wasting paper and time and causing headaches. Can this printer please be replaced? We depend on that lab for research purposes and having a solid, dependable printer would be awesome. Thanks for listening.
Thanks
Retain Oncourse for at least two more years.
Wireless network could improve more in the cavanaugh building.  I get disconnected a lot no matter what floor I am in.

the canvas usability design is not straight forward at times you looing for the navigation bar e.g discussion  bar cant be easily located and so on in short the whole design is not simple unlike that of last semester simple and straightforward easy navigation

Better wifi on campus;  better software downloads (i.e. standalone versions - I work in the field, I cannot always be connected to the internet); an email provider beside microsoft (outlook sucks); course and campus websites that are user friendly.

The inbox in canvas is difficult to use. You can't search by topic and when you click on a message from the dashboard you aren't taken to the individual message. It would also be nice to be able to organize messages into folders and by importance.

The new web-based phone is extremely bad. I'm sure there is a way to make the phone work as if it's a standard landline because this is what I have at home. Also, I simply did not hear anything about videoconferencing facilities.

Having to use UITS as a "middle man" for research projects that utilize technology services made the process much slower and clunky and resulted in an error that meant a dramatic overcharge from the third party (requiring a lengthy refund process). Plus we had to pay UITS for this additional hassle out of our research funds. Streamlining this process would be appreciated or careful consideration of the role UITS plays in research related services would be helpful.

Exchange server sometimes crashes and has difficulty connecting to Outlook on my local computer, which can be annoying and affect my efficiency at work.Also, the IU Secure wireless network does not work or performs very slowly in certain locations on campus (specifically the Barnes and Noble at the Campus Center and the Herron Student Services Office). This becomes an annoyance when I have to work with students in my office that are trying to connect to IT services from their portable devices. It would greatly improve my experience if wireless connectivity was increased throughout the IUPUI campus.Thanks for all the work that you do for the university, and for allowing me to have a voice when it comes to IT on campus.
I cannot even connect to the WiFi on my phone
None

I hate the transition from my old mail system to the Microsoft system....   it is VERY much slower than the text based system I used and it takes MUCH longer to read and dispose of my email.  I find it VERY slow to get my account started in classrooms and the software started that I need to teach... I'm not sure why it has to load all this "desktop stuff" so slowly I use the same machines every class period in the same room as last week, log in with the same ID and it seems to act like it has never seen me beforeSince I have no choice, I use the services for instruction and normal day to day activities, but I find much of the "service" to be slow and cumbersome, so I try to AVOID using UITS services as much as possible.   A prime example was my use of Echo for recording my classes.  I would REALLY like to do something like this routinely but EDITING Echo took hours and I've dropped it completely... I'm looking for an off campus vendor where I can do this on my own hardware and software because my experience with ECHO was SO BAD and I don't even have the files I created because you "OWN" them and have probably destroyed them by now.  I find this EXTREMELY inconvenient and NOT to be serving the facutly and the teaching effort effectively.

Being able to call 274-HELP is very helpful and the people I talk to have been able to help me through my problems each time. I'm sure you don't pay them enough! Wireless will never be fast enough. I appreciate all that you do to keep us connected!
N/A
Easier guest access to wifi. More reliable polygon. More user friendly kfs, time sheet, and purchasing interfaces.
Keep up the good work. It's not easy to support such a big campus and Univ system. Kudos to the men and women on the ground day in and day out!  Love you all!
n/a

Sometimes I email ithelp providing a phishing attempt and the full mail header. I am always disappointed with the reply. What I expect is for them to say something like this: "1. Thank you for reporting this phishing attempt; we appreciate it. 2. Based on your feedback, we have removed the email from everyone's email account to mitigate the risk. 3. We have adjusted our spam filter to prevent similar emails getting through in the future." What I get instead is some generic nonsense that could have been written by someone at a call center in the Philippines. The main point is that ithelp should not be a human manual. Rather, ithelp should be the go to people who actually fix problems.
not any.

Overall, UITS does a very good job, certainly the best of any of the three universities at which I've taught. Web for departments is horrid, exacerbated by the branding demand, though that probably isn't a UITS decision. Something needs to happen to make it easier for departments to have direct access to their own department pages.

I have extremely helpful co-workers who have trained me on the WCMS and Cision/Vocus systems among others, but I am super-surprised there is no official training. I ignored the photo system entirely, as I heard we're getting a new one, and I will eagerly attend that training. Every session I've gone to, whether in person or teleconference, has been excellent and informative.
I would like to see even more software in iuware, I feel like the same software has been there for some time.
Additional PC workstations for student use on the Indianapolis campus would be nice.  There seems to be an inadequate number of PCs where seating is available.
My academic advisor doesn't know what she is doing.
The issues with Outlook have been incredibly disruptive and problematic. We have lost incalculable hours of productivity.

It is very hard to log out of the box system. Or log others out so you can log on yourself. It's ridiculous. It's supposed to be secure, but it just remembers the last person who was on and keeps logging THEM back on. Seriously?
experiencing long delays in internet connectivity.
I very much dislike that AT&T is the wireless that tries to connect first no matter the times that I go to IU Secure as my first option. It drops constantly.
I had a great experience working with UITS Outreach.  They were very helpful and were able to provide a great resource to my students during orientation.
I'd like to see Adobe FrameMaker added to the Uware.
I would request for increase of surveillance camera especially in the parking lots.

It has been very frustrating that for the past couple of semesters that all of my courses have been taught through Canvas and now this semester I have an older professor (who is not tech savvy) teaching through Oncourse. I thought it had been retired when OneStart was retired and wished that they had both been shut down simultaneously. It is a lot easier to have everything all in one location when you are a full-time student juggling 4 or more classes and a work and family life.

Wi-fi in Undergraduate library is choppy and very bad at the cubicles on 3rd and 4th floors. The desktop computers take too long to log in (4 minutes or longer!). The hobos leave a stink on the keyboards, mice, and chairs. Please provide sani-wipes at all computer clusters and by the cubicles.
The wifi could get attention to try and make it more applicable to use on campus. Barely supports devices.

No suggestions, I think you guys do an incredible job!  I get such personal service from people like Mike Scott, Bill Stuckey, Joy Kramer, Nate Paritz with Echo 360, Randy - tech guy for Liberal Arts who comes to my class whenever I have problems, Dr. Amirpoorian - who visited my class to make sure all was working, and all the men and women who man the telephones at 274-HELP - Chris, Zachary, etc.  You have been there quickly every time I have had a problem.  You have always found a resolution to the problem.  And you have always treated me with kindness and understanding.  YOU GUYS ARE FANTASTIC!!!!!

Would love to be able to consult with UITS to set up on-line data storage and backup. What software to use, how to accomplish from off-site, etc. Takes too long to wade through the information publications.
Good job.

The remote access system/ computers needs updated.  Canvas needs inbox section inside each class instead of one inbox for all classes...possibly could have both.  Cell service is horrible in basements everywhere on campus-needs fixed.  the: find a printer for personal laptops at iupui needs redone to make it a whole lot more user friendly. the design in general in the basement of ET, SL, and LD buildings is depressing and needs updated.  color brings imagination and inspires people.have some of the art students redo all that.  the computer rooms need hand sanitizer stations-which will cut down on people getting sick.  ET Basement needs water bottle refill stations.
Continue the good work. I have been in other university situations and UITS' services are unparalleled.
Canvas support should be enhanced so that the UITS help line can provide immediate assistance.
great!

I do feel there is some structure that could use updating but over all its good. I also understand that iupui has a budget and needs to make money so with that iupui is doing great for what it has to use.

I work in the basement computer classrooms in Cavanaugh, and there appears to be some trouble keeping up with the wear and tear of the equipment.  I would avoid adding complicated equipment or software and focusing on working with basic systems that can be easily repaired and overcome with on the spot trouble shooting.  Fancy bells and whistles will not be as effective as good, solid interaction with the equipment and the technology.  Avoid the blindness that can come from thinking that the latest technological gadgets equals effective learning.  As you know, the technology should serve rather than we serve what "interests" the technology (or what the technology demands in terms of practice).

When we make a request for IT support that requires someone to come up and assist, it would be better if the new students who are still learning were sent with an older student who knows what they are doing. The process right now when the new students have to figure it out on their own is tedious.  It takes too much time on things that would not take that much time to fix if someone was there to help them.

CAITS is terrible to work with. (see exceptions below) We, at the Dental School (including Dean Williams) have contacted them numerous times since late 2013 to come up with a workable solution to the Dental School's intranet Roster Builder database. We used this program to provide instructors with photo rosters of students and staff and to send HIPPA protected information to the right person and avoid $10,000 (or more) per occurrence fines to the school. Instructors, faculty, and staff have all asked for it to be fixed. Nothing happens. Vince Sheehan is aware of this and we still wait. The exceptions to CAITS failure are the staff at the Dental School. Jeremy, Chris, and Joe all take ownership of their clients needs. Even under times of heavy traffic in their office, they maintain their professionalism and continue to be empathetic in servicing the needs of clients.
n/a

The wifi is always slow and difficult to connect to in places such as the Natatorium. It makes it difficult to get things done. Canvas is much more frustrating to navigate with less features than oncourse.

OneIU would be so much better if, after entering the site via login and password, the user would not have to re-enter login & password information again for any other application.  As it exists, I don't understand why I need to log into OneIU as it doesn't appear to offer any benefits.  Canvas is currently experiencing anomalies with the SpeedGrader.  They have been working on it for the past week and posted a fix but it continues to be unreliable.  Also, Canvas is not improving / changing as fast as I thought it would, given all of the feedback it solicits.

The telephone transfer-a-call process is super slow, takes too many button pushes for each task, and will transfer a call to a cell phone even though you dial a 7 digit campus number---something to do with personal Lync contact entries.
Sean Moser is the BEST!
Bring back onestart; One.IU is terrible and geared more towards mobile divices.

I am in a 3 year graduate program.  I have 3 separate IU emails that have to be checked and three different platforms being used by professors.  Everything should be in one place with the ability forward emails to my personal account.  I realize that emails are supposed to be forwarded but the IT department couldn't figure out how to make it work with my accounts.  I have missed import information for classes due to the disorganization of the IT system. It is simply a mess.  Professors shouldn't be able to choose which system they use during the transfer, it isn't fair to students.  Students should be the primary focus of the university!

1)  One.iu is an abomination.  (a) I have no need of IU Bloomington information so it's presence just adds clutter and confusion. (b) The interface is utterly idiotic.  Why would I, a professional in my field, care how popular an application is to the entire university environment?  We don't have the same needs. (c) It's almost impossible to find anything. (d) All the GUI space is wasted by using large "buttons" with virtually no information on them.  I'm not using a smartphone.  I'm using an extremely powerful desktop computer at work, and a decent laptop at home.  In neither case do I need or want to interact through an inefficient and ineffective process designed for smart phones.  (d) Stop showing me all sorts of ridiculous things I have no need of.  I'm faculty.  I don't need to see applications that are for students and staff.  In fact, except for a very few university services like SIS, I do not need any of the garbage available.  I am internet literate so if I want the weather I will go to Unisys weather (one of the services available for use by pilots) and check it myself. (e) contrast is poor on a lot of the GUI  (f) In Onestart, the options I saw were based on my needs.  One.iu is just an extremely ill-advised attempt to make everyone use the same system regardless of their divergent needs.  This is not progress -- it is regression.  In fact, If you were to compare my satisfaction with UITS three years ago to today, you'd find that it has plummeted from quite a high level to previously unimaginable depths.2) I am extremely unhappy about the consolidation of services in Bloomington.  That leads to wrong answers to questions from IUPUI, and directions to the wrong forms and sites.  It also leads to long delays.  Apparently IUB calls get priority over ours.  One time I was told "3 calls ahead of you...", "two calls ahead of you..."  "one call ahead of you..."  "two calls ahead of you... "one call ahead of you..."  "two calls ahead of you..."  As if that weren't bad enough, in the last few days, I have had trouble getting any of the Bloomington UITS staff to even answer their phones or email at all.  I need access to mercury to transfer an organizational website from our school's servers.  My  group account has an account on mercury, as do I.  A call to UITS established (over a couple hours) that the fault was not mine.  After approximately four hours (no exaggeration) of emails and phone calls  I was finally able to get someone in Tier 2 service to fix my account (which I did not actually care about at the moment) and I am still waiting for the group account to be fixed.  (My request clearly stated that it was the group account I needed to access immediately.)  I'm told a single person is handling all webmaster requests and there are hundreds.  If true, how could any service possibly be so badly managed?  I'm not asking for something exotic.  I need to transfer a simple website that works in another location to another and I can't even log on!     UITS is making me look bad. I was supposed to transfer this website on a particular date. No one could even imagine that UITS would be incapable of handling facilitating something so simple.  I made sure I had requested and obtained the account well in advance, so that I would be ready as soon as the website upgrades were done.  I don't appreciate being made to look incompetent when the incompetence is someone else's!In summary, the quality of customer service and computing services provided by UITS has plummeted over the past couple of years.  None of the changes constitute progress.  I cannot imagine what those in charge of UITS are thinking.  More importantly, what the heck are people doing?  How can it be possible that a simple problem cannot be solved within minutes?  Not to mention that this problem should never have occurred in the first place.

The areas with rows and rows of computers is not a comfortable space.  For example, law library 2nd floor - everyone can see everyone else's work. Kiosks  - not all of us are 6 feet tall and anything we look up on those, can be seen by everyone. Also, library 3rd and 4th floors - not enough work space around the computer.  Lastly, IT building UITS same problem that anyone walking past can see your work. Isn't there a way to put something on the screen to avoid this or design the space better?

I would love for more standing desk options in the school of medicine and at Riley. I wish that we would totally switch do a different browser versus explorer as the preferred. Many sites are not able to be read by explorer due to the outdated nature of the software. I also wish some things were more MAC friendly. I will say that IT is always willing to help and always polite. I have had experiences with other organizations where this is not available.

Sometimes, when printing, there will be black lines running down the page. When this happens, I will have to go print at another printer to get a clean copy. I know that there are a lot of printers to keep up with, and I am not sure what the problem is to cause it or I would offer a solution.  But, I wanted to bring it to your attention.
Great job!

Wifi is terrible here.  CFS employees are issued iPhones that cannot contact emergency assistance if needed.  Some of the duties we perform are high risk, and it is discouraging to know that help may be extremely delayed or not arrive at all.  Thanks for asking, I hope someone looks into it.

Something MUST be done with the functionality of Outlook and the servers on the IU campus. This has been going on for months and months and has to be literally costing hundreds of thousands of lost time in productivity. COUNTLESS times a week, you click on an item in outlook and it sends the system in to a spiral and you are left with your computer "Not Responding" for 5-10 minutes at a time. This happens 8-10 times a day some days and occasionally you are left with no choice but to reboot. They say to report when this happens - but happens SO frequently anymore I feel this is all I would be doing all day. You literally hear people shout from there desks "come on" - you know their computer is stuck yet again. I feel that as a higher education institution this is inexcusable. I could see that it might happen initially and then a fix would take place - this has been going on for months and months and is SUPER frustrating and a giant failure in the system if you ask me.

Some of these items sound familiar, but I could not state any level of satisfaction since my knowledge of the service is limited.Overall I appreciate the effort and service provided by UITS.  Thanks!
Our office mainly works with the CAITS group.
Very good followup services.

Please get rid of Movi/jabber/pexip/video bridge. It is a horrible videoconferencing system that is unreliable and consistently drops users. Support services need to be more streamlined (SIS, Canvas, Box, ect.) As a Visual Communocation Design major, I find the UI/UX design of most of these services simply awful, especially the new Canvas design. The original Canvas navigation design was much more user friendly, despite not looking as nice. Overall, most of the programs are not easy to navigate and there are too many programs to keep track of. Between them all, there's no streamlined design to make them feel cohesive. One.IU was an obvious attempt  to fix that issue, and it's a step in the right direction, but until all the programs have similar interfaces they will continue to read as a group of unrelated programs we have to deal with to do simple tasks.  Stop these drawn out phase-outs of programs like Oncourse and Onestart. It's really inconvenient when a few profs are using Oncourse (looking at you, CS department!) And the rest have integrated to Canvas already. From a designer's POV, I understand the want to phase these things out in a way that will make people comfortable, but forcing them to adapt quickly (instead of letting them continue to use outdated software until it's really gone, and making them adapt months later than everyone else) will result in a much smoother transition later down the road, despite being a bit bumpy at the start. Everyone complains when Facebook updates it's look, but they get used to it after a week and you you never hear another complaint (until another update). If users were allowed to phase out their Facebook UI whenever they wanted, they simply wouldn't.  Then, when you force them to, they'll complain months after everyone else and it gets drawn out instead of one week of public backlash, you feel
